The relation in which the accusative stands to the verb with which it is constructed depends upon the meaning ol the verb. The main distinction to be drawn is between the accusatives ol the External and Internal object. In the one the action of the verb is directed to something outside of, and distinct j lrom the meaning ol the verb; in the other the accusative ἵ repeats more or less completely the meaning ol the verb. For instance in ε’λκοε ὅ με οὔτασε the acc. ἕλκος repeats the meaning contained in οὔτασε and may be called internal‚ while με’ is altogether distinct from and outside the meaning of the verb and may be called external.
